{
  "texts": [
    "Initial attempts to give 90% weight to execution time and 10% to diversity led to suboptimal performance, as the diversity metric was excessively minimized, diminishing the overall robustness of the system.",
    "Specifically, the observed diversity values were lower than expected, and the exploration of the solution space by the RL algorithm was insufficiently Algorithm 1 Estimating WCET with RL and Moving Average Check1: Initialize Environment 2: Choose the environment based on the case study 3: Initialize observation and action spaces 4: Train RL Model 5: Set total timesteps for training 6: Initialize moving average variables for each timestep do 7: end for Sample an action from the action space 8:For CD, generate two random ints between 0 and 7 9:For the 6-DOF, generate one random int between 1 and 63 10:Execute action in the environment (based on the integer(s) generated, select the corresponding movement for the foundational or joint angles for the 6-DOF case study)11: Find reward by calculating weighted average of execution time and diversity 12: Observe reward and next state 13: Update RL model 14: Update total rewards and step count if step count reaches window size then 15: end if Calculate moving average of rewards if moving average shows insufficient improvement then 16: end if Increment no improvement count else 17: end if Reset no improvement count 18: Reset total rewards and step count if no improvement count exceeds the max allowed then 19: end if Break from training loop 20: Save the trained model Algorithm 2 Estimating WCET with RL and Moving Average Check 1: Evaluate RL Model 2: Load the trained model 3: Reset environment for each evaluation episode do 4: end for Predict action from the current state 5: Execute action in the environment 6: Observe reward, next state, and whether episode is done if episode is done then 7: end if Record maximum reward and related state and action 8: Reset environment for next episode 9: return Results 10: Display maximum reward and corresponding state and action 11:Plot reward history over time comprehensive.",
    "When the weight was adjusted to 70% for execution time, the results indicated that insufficient emphasis was being placed on execution time, leading to less accurate estimations of WCET.",
    "The final balance of 80% weight for execution time proved to offer the best trade-off, as it allowed for sufficient consideration of both factors while maintaining a focus on efficient task completion.The specific details related to applying RL to each of the case studies are explained in the following two subsections.",
    "Case Study• Observation Space: In CD case study, the observation space is defined by the positions of objects, represented as a nine-dimensional vector."
